T1  - REGULATING INSURANCE MARKETS: MULTIPLE CONTRACTING AND ADVERSE SELECTION
AU  - Attar, Andrea
AU  - Mariotti, Thomas
AU  - Salanié, François
Y1  - 2022/08/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12570
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 981
EP  - 1020
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12570
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract This article studies an insurance market on which privately informed consumers can simultaneously trade with several firms operating under a regulation that prohibits cross-subsidies between contracts. The regulated game supports a single equilibrium allocation in which each layer of coverage is fairly priced given the consumer types who purchase it. This competitive allocation cannot be Pareto-improved by a social planner who observes neither consumers' types nor their trades with firms. Public intervention under multiple contracting and adverse selection should thus arguably target firms' pricing strategies, leaving consumers free to choose their preferred amount of coverage.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - FINANCING VENTURES
AU  - Greenwood, Jeremy
AU  - Han, Pengfei
AU  - Sánchez, Juan M.
Y1  - 2022/08/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12561
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1021
EP  - 1053
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12561
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract The relationship between venture capital (VC) and growth is examined using an endogenous growth model incorporating dynamic contracts between entrepreneurs and venture capitalists. At each stage of financing, venture capitalists evaluate the viability of startups. If viable, venture capitalists provide funding for the next stage. The success of a project depends on the amount of funding. The model is confronted with stylized facts about VC: statistics by funding round concerning success rates, failure rates, investment rates, equity shares, and initial public offering values. The increased efficiency offered by VC for financing inventive startups is important for long-run growth and welfare.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - FLEXIBILITY AND PRODUCTIVITY: TOWARD THE UNDERSTANDING OF FIRM HETEROGENEITY
AU  - Macedoni, Luca
AU  - Xu, Mingzhi (Jimmy)
Y1  - 2022/08/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12563
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1055
EP  - 1108
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12563
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We document four new stylized facts using Chinese firm-level data to show that the standard single-attribute model of trade, in which firms only differ in productivity, must be augmented with an additional layer of heterogeneity to match the facts. To match the evidence, a model requires heterogeneity in flexibility, namely, the ability to introduce new varieties in a destination at low costs. We calibrate our model and find suggestive evidence of a trade-off between productivity and flexibility. Furthermore, we show that ignoring firm flexibility causes a large underestimation of the welfare effects of trade.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - AUCTIONS FOR CHARITY: THE CURSE OF THE FAMILIAR
AU  - Carpenter, Jeffrey
AU  - Damianov, Damian S.
AU  - Matthews, Peter Hans
Y1  - 2022/08/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12559
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1109
EP  - 1135
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12559
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Auctions and raffles are commonly used to fund public goods. We run fundraising events in the field at the meetings of a well-known service organization across the United States to examine the fundraising properties of five mechanisms: one that is common in the literature, two that are familiar to practitioners in the field, and two that are new. Consistent with a novel model assuming independent private attachments to the charity, we find large differences in the performance between the two most familiar formats, but these disparities are dwarfed by the differentials achieved using the new and less common formats.
ER  - 

