T1  - FIRM EXPORT DYNAMICS AND THE EXCHANGE RATE: A QUANTITATIVE EXPLORATION
AU  - Lopez-Martin, Bernabe
Y1  - 2022/08/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12572
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1137
EP  - 1163
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12572
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract This article provides a theoretical model of firm dynamics that replicates the export elasticity values estimated in the empirical literature, and the heterogeneous response of firms. The analysis of alternative versions of the model allows for a decomposition of the contributions of the different mechanisms (distribution costs, imported intermediate inputs, gradual growth of foreign demand, and market access costs in foreign/domestic currency). Distribution costs represent the most important factor to replicate elasticity estimations. Furthermore, distribution costs allow the model to replicate the heterogeneous response of exports to exchange rate movements by decreasing the demand elasticity of more productive firms.
ER  - 

