T1  - CHINA'S HOUSING BUBBLE, INFRASTRUCTURE INVESTMENT, AND ECONOMIC GROWTH
AU  - Jiang, Shenzhe
AU  - Miao, Jianjun
AU  - Zhang, Yuzhe
Y1  - 2022/08/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12562
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1189
EP  - 1237
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12562
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract China's housing prices have been growing rapidly over the past few decades, despite low growth in rents. We study the impact of housing bubbles on China's economy, based on the understanding that local governments use land-sale revenue to fuel infrastructure investment. We calibrate our model to the Chinese data over the period 2003?13 and find that our calibrated model can match the declining capital return and GDP growth, the average housing price growth, and the rising infrastructure to GDP ratio in the data. We conduct two counterfactual experiments to estimate the impact of a bubble collapse and a property tax.
ER  - 

