T1  - THE CHANGING STRUCTURE OF GOVERNMENT CONSUMPTION SPENDING
AU  - Moro, Alessio
AU  - Rachedi, Omar
Y1  - 2022/08/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12568
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1293
EP  - 1323
VL  - 63
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12568
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We document a secular change in the structure of government consumption spending: Over time the government purchases relatively more private-sector goods, and relies less on its own production of value added. This process alters the transmission of fiscal policy, by dampening the response of hours, public value added, and the labor share to government spending shocks, while leaving the response of total output unchanged. We rationalize these facts in a general equilibrium model where a decline of the public-sector relative productivity drives the changing structure of government spending, which in turn modifies the transmission mechanism of government spending shocks.
ER  - 

